However, the goddess of truth, Verita, saw the deceit. She did not strike Jaxen down but cursed him: every lie he spoke would turn to gold dust in his mouth. At first, Jaxen rejoiced, thinking he would be rich. But the gold was heavy, choking him with every falsehood. To breathe, he had to cough up the wealth, but the villagers learned that to claim the gold, they had to listen to his lies, which poisoned their minds with distrust.

The village elders realized the cost of punishing Jaxen was their own unity. The gold brought greed, and the lies brought discord. To end the cycle, they made a solemn pact: they would ignore Jaxen completely. Without an audience to deceive or gold to be gathered, the curse lost its power. Jaxen wandered into the wilderness, silenced not by force, but by indifference.
